The possible integer roots are the divisors of 6: \(\pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3, \pm 6\). We need to consider all sets of three distinct integers whose product is \(-6\). These sets are: 1. \((-1, 1, 6)\) 2. \((-1, 2, 3)\) 3. \((-2, 1, 3)\) 4. \((-3, 1, 2)\) 5. \((-1, -2, -3)\) For each set of roots, we calculate the coefficients \(a\) and \(b\) using the sums and products of the roots: - The coefficient \(a\) is the negative of the sum of the roots. - The coefficient \(b\) is the sum of the products of the roots taken two at a time. Calculations for each set: 1. Roots \((-1, 1, 6)\): - Sum: \(-1 + 1 + 6 = 6\) �� \(a = -6\) - Product pairs: \((-1 \cdot 1) + (-1 \cdot 6) + (1 \cdot 6) = -1 - 6 + 6 = -1\) �� \(b = -1\) - Ordered pair: \((-6, -1)\) 2. Roots \((-1, 2, 3)\): - Sum: \(-1 + 2 + 3 = 4\) �� \(a = -4\) - Product pairs: \((-1 \cdot 2) + (-1 \cdot 3) + (2 \cdot 3) = -2 - 3 + 6 = 1\) �� \(b = 1\) - Ordered pair: \((-4, 1)\) 3. Roots \((-2, 1, 3)\): - Sum: \(-2 + 1 + 3 = 2\) �� \(a = -2\) - Product pairs: \((-2 \cdot 1) + (-2 \cdot 3) + (1 \cdot 3) = -2 - 6 + 3 = -5\) �� \(b = -5\) - Ordered pair: \((-2, -5)\) 4. Roots \((-3, 1, 2)\): - Sum: \(-3 + 1 + 2 = 0\) �� \(a = 0\) - Product pairs: \((-3 \cdot 1) + (-3 \cdot 2) + (1 \cdot 2) = -3 - 6 + 2 = -7\) �� \(b = -7\) - Ordered pair: \((0, -7)\) 5. Roots \((-1, -2, -3)\): - Sum: \(-1 + (-2) + (-3) = -6\) �� \(a = 6\) - Product pairs: \((-1 \cdot -2) + (-1 \cdot -3) + (-2 \cdot -3) = 2 + 3 + 6 = 11\) �� \(b = 11\) - Ordered pair: \((6, 11)\) Thus, the ordered pairs \((a, b)\) are \((-6, -1)\), \((-4, 1)\), \((-2, -5)\), \((0, -7)\), and \((6, 11)\), leading to a total of 5 distinct ordered pairs. \[ \boxed{5} \]
